  "name": "Norton-Simon kill on Gompertz growth (NSCLC)",
  "description": "A drug-effect (kill) model embodying the Norton-Simon hypothesis: the drug-induced regression rate is proportional to the unperturbed GROWTH rate, so a smaller, faster-growing tumor is more chemo-sensitive than a large one near carrying capacity. On a Gompertz growth law: dV/dt = (g - k*E)*V*ln(Vmax/V). This is mechanistically distinct from the log-kill assumption (kill proportional to tumor size) used by the Claret model — including it lets the divergence view quantify how much the assumed kill mechanism, not just the parameters, moves the survival prediction. Parameterized for first-line NSCLC. Values illustrative and unverified.",
  "kernel": "norton_simon",
  "structure": {
    "growth_law": "gompertz",
